<Base title="Rivian 2026 — Adam Crespi" description="Embedded Software Intern at Rivian, Platform Functional Safety team.">
  <main>
    <a class="back" href="/">Adam Crespi</a>

    <h1 class="ptitle">Embedded Software at Rivian</h1>
    <p class="meta">May 2026 – August 2026 · Platform Functional Safety · Palo Alto, CA</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <article class="prose">
      <p>Returning to Rivian on the Platform Functional Safety team, working on RAI-OS — Rivian's safety-critical embedded OS built on FreeRTOS targeting Armv7-R (Cortex-R5F) microcontrollers.</p>

      <h2>What I worked on</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Kernel measurement engine</strong> — architected a FreeRTOS-native benchmarking harness where each kernel operation is described once as an isolated setup-operation-teardown probe driven by two interchangeable runners: a fixed-window throughput counter (ops/window regression signal) and a single-shot latency sampler producing min/median/p99/max cycle distributions. Eliminates the dual-codebase burden of maintaining separate benchmark suites and attributes any version-to-version performance drift to a specific primitive rather than a blanket slowdown.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cortex-R5F PMU cycle counter</strong> — implemented the load-bearing timing instrument using the Armv7-R Performance Monitoring Unit for sub-nanosecond resolution and near-zero read overhead, with MIN-over-N overhead self-calibration and a cross-thread timestamping mechanism for operations that span a context switch. Implemented probes across the full kernel surface: context switch, semaphore, queue/IPC, heap allocation, and ready-queue selection, including a priority-inheritance probe covering the unbounded-priority-inversion hazard that standard suites like Thread-Metric omit — directly relevant in a safety-critical kernel.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Hardware trace validation</strong> — certified the on-chip cycle-counter proxy against non-intrusive hardware trace (Lauterbach TRACE32) to quantify the interrupt-entry leg invisible to software counters. Ported the methodology from upstream Cortex-M assumptions to the Armv7-R target (VIM/GIC-pended interrupts, banked-mode context paths).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CI regression gate</strong> — wired the harness into CI as a per-version regression gate that compares each RAI-OS build against its predecessor on pinned hardware, catching performance regressions before they reach integration.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Skills</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>RTOS internals:</strong> FreeRTOS kernel modification, TCB extensions, scheduler instrumentation</li>
        <li><strong>Hardware:</strong> Armv7-R (Cortex-R5F), PMU cycle counters, ETM/CoreSight, banked register modes</li>
        <li><strong>Tooling:</strong> Lauterbach TRACE32, JTAG, CI integration, pinned-hardware regression testing</li>
        <li><strong>Safety context:</strong> functional safety, priority inversion hazards, deterministic timing</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

